---
import ArticleLayout from '../../layouts/ArticleLayout.astro';
---

<ArticleLayout
  kind="lesson"
  title="Why diversification matters"
  description="Venture outcomes follow a power law: most startups fail, a few return everything. Lesson one in the Bundle Academy core path, why professionals build portfolios instead of picking winners."
  category="Core path"
  meta="Lesson 01 · 8 min · Level 1"
  takeaways={[
    'Most early-stage startups fail, this is normal, not a scandal.',
    'Returns follow a power law: a small number of companies produce almost all the gains.',
    'You cannot reliably predict which company will be the outlier, neither can professionals.',
    'Diversification is how professionals buy exposure to the outliers without betting on naming them.',
    'Diversification reduces concentration risk. It does not remove the risk of losing money.',
  ]}
  nextLabel="Why startups fail"
  nextHref="/learn"
>
  <p>
    Here is the uncomfortable arithmetic every professional startup investor
    accepts before breakfast: <strong>most of the companies they back will
    fail.</strong> Not "underperform", fail. The money invested in them is
    usually lost entirely.
  </p>
  <p>
    This isn't because professionals are bad at picking. It's the structure of
    the asset class. Early-stage companies are experiments, and most experiments
    don't work. UK data has told the same story for decades: the majority of
    startups don't return their investors' capital.
  </p>

  <h2>The power law, in one picture</h2>
  <p>
    If startup returns were like a coin flip, some win a bit, some lose a bit, concentration would merely be risky. But they aren't. Startup returns follow
    a <strong>power law</strong>: outcomes are wildly unequal, and a tiny number
    of companies produce almost all the money.
  </p>
  <div class="callout" role="img" aria-label="Illustrative portfolio of ten startups: six return nothing, three return roughly their capital, one returns twenty times">
    <p style="margin:0 0 0.75rem"><strong>An illustrative ten-company portfolio:</strong></p>
    <div class="pl-chart">
      {
        [0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, 1, 1.5, 20].map((v, i) => (
          <div class="pl-col">
            <div class="pl-bar-zone">
              <span
                class="pl-bar"
                style={`height:${Math.max(v * 4.4, 3)}px;background:${v >= 20 ? 'var(--c1)' : v > 0 ? 'var(--chart-deemph)' : 'var(--red-tint)'};${v === 0 ? 'border:1px dashed var(--red);opacity:.7' : ''}`}
              />
            </div>
            <span class="pl-x mono">{v === 0 ? '0×' : `${v}×`}</span>
          </div>
        ))
      }
    </div>
    <p style="margin:0.75rem 0 0;font-size:0.85rem" class="muted">
      Six fail. Three roughly return their money. One returns 20×. The portfolio
      as a whole more than doubles, <em>because of one company nobody could have
      named in advance.</em> Illustrative numbers, not a forecast.
    </p>
  </div>
  <p>
    Now run the thought experiment the other way. Suppose you'd invested in just
    one of those ten companies. There's a 60% chance you lost everything, a 30%
    chance you got roughly your money back, and a 10% chance you hit the
    outlier. Same companies, same information, completely different experience,
    purely because of <em>how the capital was spread</em>.
  </p>

  <h2>"But I'll just pick the good one"</h2>
  <p>
    Everyone believes this, briefly. Here's the professional consensus you're up
    against: venture capitalists, with proprietary data rooms, reference calls,
    board seats and decades of pattern-matching, still cannot reliably name the
    outlier in advance. Their answer isn't better picking. It's
    <strong>portfolio construction</strong>: back enough credible companies that
    the power law works <em>for</em> you instead of against you.
  </p>
  <blockquote>
    Diversification is not a hedge against being wrong. It's the honest
    admission that in this asset class, everyone is wrong most of the time, and a strategy that's built to survive it.
  </blockquote>
  <p>
    This is the single biggest behavioural difference between professionals and
    retail investors in private markets. Retail platforms sell single-company
    stories: a brand you love, a founder you relate to. Professionals allocate
    across twenty or more positions, expect the failures, and size every cheque
    so no single failure matters.
  </p>

  <h2>What this means for you, practically</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Think in portfolios, not picks.</strong> Before asking "is this
      startup good?", ask "what does my overall exposure look like?"
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Size positions so failure is survivable.</strong> If losing a
      position entirely would genuinely hurt, it's too big. This is why Bundle's
      minimums are £10–£50, spreading matters more than the amount.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Spread across sectors and stages, not just companies.</strong>
      Twenty seed-stage climate startups is one bet wearing twenty costumes.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Expect failures, plural.</strong> When one arrives, it isn't the
      strategy breaking. It's the strategy's assumption arriving on schedule.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <div class="callout warn">
    <strong>The honest limit:</strong> diversification reduces concentration
    risk, the risk of one failure taking everything. It does <em>not</em> make
    startup investing safe. A diversified startup portfolio can still lose
    money, and every position in it is illiquid for years. Never invest money
    you may need back.
  </div>

  <h2>Check your understanding</h2>
  <p>Two questions, the adaptive Academy uses these to decide what to teach you next.</p>

  <div class="quiz" data-quiz>
    <fieldset class="quiz-q">
      <legend>1. In a typical early-stage portfolio, where do most of the returns come from?</legend>
      <label><input type="radio" name="q1" value="a" /> <span>Steady modest gains across most companies</span></label>
      <label><input type="radio" name="q1" value="b" data-correct /> <span>A small number of outlier companies</span></label>
      <label><input type="radio" name="q1" value="c" /> <span>Dividends paid by the profitable ones</span></label>
      <p class="quiz-fb" hidden></p>
    </fieldset>
    <fieldset class="quiz-q">
      <legend>2. Diversification means a startup portfolio can't lose money overall.</legend>
      <label><input type="radio" name="q2" value="a" /> <span>True, that's the point of spreading</span></label>
      <label><input type="radio" name="q2" value="b" data-correct /> <span>False, it reduces concentration risk, not the risk of loss</span></label>
      <p class="quiz-fb" hidden></p>
    </fieldset>
  </div>
</ArticleLayout>

<style>
  .pl-chart {
    display: flex;
    align-items: flex-end;
    gap: 6px;
  }

  .pl-col {
    flex: 1;
    display: grid;
    gap: 0.35rem;
    justify-items: center;
  }

  .pl-bar-zone {
    display: flex;
    align-items: flex-end;
    height: 96px;
  }

  .pl-bar {
    width: 100%;
    min-width: 14px;
    max-width: 24px;
    border-radius: 4px 4px 0 0;
    display: block;
  }

  .pl-x {
    font-size: 0.66rem;
    color: var(--text-2);
  }

  .quiz {
    display: grid;
    gap: 1.25rem;
    margin: 1.5rem 0 0;
  }

  .quiz-q {
    border: 1px solid var(--line);
    border-radius: var(--r-m);
    padding: 1.25rem 1.5rem;
    background: var(--surface);
    box-shadow: var(--shadow-s);
  }

  .quiz-q legend {
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--ink);
    padding: 0 0.4rem;
  }

  .quiz-q label {
    display: flex;
    gap: 0.6rem;
    align-items: flex-start;
    padding: 0.5rem 0.4rem;
    border-radius: var(--r-s);
    cursor: pointer;
    font-size: 0.98rem;
  }

  .quiz-q label:hover {
    background: var(--tint-soft);
  }

  .quiz-q input {
    margin-top: 0.3rem;
    accent-color: var(--teal);
  }

  .quiz-fb {
    margin: 0.6rem 0 0;
    padding: 0.7rem 0.9rem;
    border-radius: var(--r-s);
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    font-weight: 550;
  }

  .quiz-fb.ok {
    background: var(--sage-tint);
    color: var(--sage-ink);
  }

  .quiz-fb.no {
    background: var(--sand-tint);
    color: var(--sand-ink);
  }
</style>

<script>
  document.querySelectorAll<HTMLElement>('[data-quiz] .quiz-q').forEach((q) => {
    const fb = q.querySelector<HTMLElement>('.quiz-fb');
    q.querySelectorAll<HTMLInputElement>('input[type="radio"]').forEach((input) => {
      input.addEventListener('change', () => {
        if (!fb) return;
        const correct = input.hasAttribute('data-correct');
        fb.hidden = false;
        fb.classList.toggle('ok', correct);
        fb.classList.toggle('no', !correct);
        fb.textContent = correct
          ? 'Correct. In the live Academy, you’d move straight on.'
          : 'Not quite, reread the section above. In the live Academy, the Education Agent would teach this concept again with new examples before you continue.';
      });
    });
  });
</script>
